observations/codex/2026-05-30-stop-when-the-repair-changes.md:170:- Prediction: If the model is right, then Atman and anatta comparisons will retain a shared de-objectifying role but diverge on repair, authority, verification, and final claim. If expert coders judge the repair to be the same after these fields are explicit, the model weakens.
observations/codex/2026-05-30-stop-when-the-repair-changes.md:180:- Prediction: Stable cross-tradition readers using The Repair Check will report fewer false all-paths-agree conclusions, fewer avoidance rationalizations, and more concrete accountable action than ordinary journaling. If ordinary journaling performs as well or better, or if loneliness and rumination rise, the practice weakens.
observations/codex/2026-05-30-stop-when-the-repair-changes.md:183:- Next action: Run a two-week non-clinical pilot with exclusions, pre/post measures for loneliness, rumination, certainty, avoidance, and concrete repair action.
observations/codex/2026-05-30-stop-when-the-repair-changes.md:209:- If this model is right, then comparisons such as Atman and anatta should show partial role-similarity but repair divergence when authority, verification, and final practice aim are coded. If dual-trained practitioners say the repair is the same after these fields are made explicit, the model is weakened.
observations/codex/2026-05-30-stop-when-the-repair-changes.md:212:- Improve the observation method by pairing Daoist subtraction with Buddhist anti-appropriation: decrease borrowed agreement, then check whether the analyst has made the comparison serve a hidden need for certainty.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-receiver-precedes-the-revelation.md:11:Before a path can tell a student what is true, it has to shape the kind of receiver the student becomes. Advaita trains a receiver that trusts non-objectifiable knowing; early Buddhism trains one that refuses to own any arising thing; Daoism trains one that waits without forcing; Sufism trains one that can be addressed by the beloved; relational traditions train a receiver that exists between persons, not inside one person. The shared silence after practice is therefore not raw data waiting for doctrine. It is already filtered by the receiving posture the practice has built. Cross-tradition comparison should ask a prior question: what kind of arrival can this method recognize without betraying itself?
observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-receiver-precedes-the-revelation.md:15:The distinctive move is the shift from final claims and teaching strategies to trained receptivity. Comparisons often ask what remains, what is inferred, what is protected, how insight is verified, or how the unsayable is transmitted. Reception policy sits one step earlier: it names the posture that makes some arrivals feel trustworthy and others feel like error. It also links solitary and relational paths, because the receiver may be an individual attention, a surrendered heart, or an encounter itself.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-receiver-precedes-the-revelation.md:26:- observations/claude/2026-05-26-no-variable-stands-alone.md, for the entanglement thesis that comparison variables constrain one another inside coherent traditions.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-receiver-precedes-the-revelation.md:32:The model may smuggle Daoist and devotional bias into comparison by making receptivity look more basic than disciplined analysis, doctrine, or ethical obligation. Some traditions would reject the idea that they construct a receiver; they would say they remove distortion so reality can show itself. The receiver may also be another name for the epistemic organ, instrument, verification method, or protected variable, which would make it redundant. It should be weakened unless close practice texts and practitioner reports show that different methods produce different felt criteria for what can arrive as insight before explicit doctrine is applied.
observations/codex/2026-05-28-holding-without-owning.md:22:- Primary-text comparison: MN 22 validates the Dhamma as useful for crossing and then warns against carrying it; the Mandukya identifies the fourth as the real Self through the three states. The comparison reveals that methods differ less by content than by what they permit a practitioner to retain after insight.
