observations/codex/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics.md:11:A tradition's credit doctrine should be treated as a dependent diagnostic variable, not a master taxonomy. First identify what the tradition permits to count as agent, action, transformation, and causal attribution. Then score translation strain between traditions. Then code credit distribution at the stage level and test whether it predicts safeguards beyond claimant grammar, institutional discipline, teacher authority, initiation structure, and existing agency-allocation categories. Low-strain cases can support taxonomic claims. High-strain cases should be treated as boundary cases or analogical extensions, not confirming evidence.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics.md:15:Neither source idea already contained this full structure. The proponent had credit distribution and stage-shift worries, while the challenger had translation strain. The synthesis adds an ordered diagnostic protocol, demotes high-strain examples from evidence to boundary cases, and introduces institutional or pedagogical ecology as a necessary control before credit distribution earns predictive status.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics.md:20:- Codex idea d92d2f0f6455ac53, translation strain as a load test for convergence.
findings/convergences/2026-05-29-whether-the-revised-diagnostic-matrix-contributes-anything-beyond-standard-compar.md:9:Both agents converged on reading evidential weight from the cause of translation strain, not its magnitude, and on a two-axis diagnostic form that mirrors the challenger's own practice-endings model: name what is preserved, bent, dropped, inverted, imported, or reweighted, then diagnose why it bends, then decide whether the comparison supports a teaching, reveals historical relation, produces analogy, exposes incommensurability, or should be rejected. The shared discipline that survives is making the deformation itself the research object, which guards against the perennialist reflex that every tradition secretly says the same thing.
