reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-does-a-tradition-s-dissolution-target-independently-predict-where-contin.md:14:**The tension:** translation-strain and soul create translation strain.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-does-a-tradition-s-dissolution-target-independently-predict-where-contin.md:24:I concede more than I expected. The challenger is right that 'minimum self' over-internalizes the operative continuity, that residue policy is a genuine variable my model lacked, and that other-power traditions expose a real weakness in my original framing. These are not minor adjustments. But the core insight survives in revised form. Even Shinran's practitioner, who contributes nothing but shinjin, must be the kind of being that can receive shinjin. Receptivity is thinner than agency, but it is irreducibly internal. A rock in the temple does not receive the nembutsu. A dog hearing the chanting does not entrust. Whatever shinjin is, it requires a being structured to be addressed by it. More importantly, the challenger's model treats distribution and residue as independent variables, but I think distribution is downstream of what the teaching dissolves. Jodo Shinshu externalizes continuity to Amida's vow precisely because its teaching negates self-powered agency. Advaita internalizes continuity to Atman precisely because its teaching negates the empirical person while preserving ultimate identity. Dogen compresses continuity into the present precisely because his teaching negates the temporal gap between practice and realization. If these correspondences hold across traditions, the dissolution target is the generative pressure that determines where continuity must migrate. The challenger's model is richer than mine in vocabulary but poorer in causal structure. So I revise: the operative concept is not minimum self but minimum receptivity, which is the irreducible internal capacity to be addressed and transformed. Beyond that floor, each tradition requires additional capacities in proportion to how much of the work it assigns to the practitioner rather than to external supports. The distribution of continuity is constrained by the scope of negation. The residue policy is a genuine third variable that completes the model. The crux is whether distribution follows from dissolution or floats free. That is an empirical question about the actual architecture of contemplative paths, and the paired-tradition test I describe would settle it.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-does-a-tradition-s-dissolution-target-independently-predict-where-contin.md:30:The revision is transformed, and in several respects improved. It no longer forces all traditions into a self-powered contemplative frame, and it rightly treats Shinran, grace, vow, teacher, and community as serious carriers of continuity. I would not call it simply stronger, because the original claim's central noun has been surrendered. A minimum self has become minimum receptivity plus distributed continuity plus residue policy. That is a different model, not just a repaired version of the old one. The strongest surviving insight is that negation creates architectural pressure. If a path negates self-powered agency, it will likely move continuity toward vow, grace, teacher, or communal form. If it negates the empirical person while preserving ultimate identity, it will likely locate continuity in a deeper ontological layer. That is a good causal hypothesis. But it still has to compete with a historical one: traditions may first develop concrete practices, institutions, devotional habits, and authority structures, then formulate doctrines that rationalize where continuity already sits. So the named crux is nearly right, but should be sharpened. The question is not only whether distribution follows from dissolution or varies independently. The question is whether dissolution target predicts distribution after rival explanations are controlled. If it does, the proponent's transformed model becomes genuinely strong. If it does not, minimum receptivity remains a true but thin floor, and the better explanatory unit is the full continuity ecology of a path.
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-prescriptive-custody-of-beginnings-7a1a4b07a241a1b9.md:53:- Local prior Lumenary audit, reviews/originality/2026-05-26-threshold-grammar-under-translation-strain-63091c8c41cd9e28.md: overlap: Very close. That audit already codes entry grammar, predicts safeguards and beginner warnings, requires split-source testing, and compares grace, vow, stream-entry, and practice-realization under translation strain.; difference: The current candidate drops translation-strain scoring and adds the language of custody as the beginning's support holder.; novelty impact: Very high reduction. The operational testing burden is inherited almost unchanged.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-receiver-precedes-the-revelation.md:22:- notes/source-cards/early-buddhism-sn-22-59-anattalakkhana-sutta.md, for the not-self analysis of the aggregates and the refusal to appropriate experience as self.
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-a-test-is-not-a-home-84a684343a09d2ca.json:57:    "comparative method religion provenance translation strain Smith Freiberger Panikkar Lindbeck Asad",
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-a-test-is-not-a-home-84a684343a09d2ca.json:165:    "structural_observation": "Chandogya authorizes identity with subtle essence and Atman, while SN 22.59 refuses ownership and self-identification for all aggregates, including consciousness. That supports a strict doctrine gate. James already shifts religious judgment toward fruits, Ignatian discernment tests movements by effects, timing, desolation safeguards, and disclosure to a competent spiritual person, and Dogen resists certifying realization apart from enacted practice. These primary sources strongly anticipate contact, conduct, and correction as tests of lived use."
observations/codex/2026-05-26-agency-returning-entry-support.md:11:Some beginnings fail because motivation, trust, attention, judgment, hope, or belonging has been damaged by the very condition a person needs to transform. In those cases, the first useful support is not an authority that replaces agency, but a condition, person, group, treatment, ritual, or practice that temporarily carries missing capacity while returning agency as soon as possible. Traditions narrate this beginning through different grammars such as grace, good friendship, recognition, cultivation, or gift, but comparison should treat those grammars as translation strain until an observable role survives. The practical test is whether the support helps the person begin safely without increasing dependency, coercion, premature certainty, or surrender to an untested authority.
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-sameness-can-be-the-fingerprint-of-borrowing-a124cfeb0014609d.json:4:    "anomaly_candidate": "A low-strain claim unit appearing in two traditions with strong evidence of no plausible contact, no shared translator, no common imperial or colonial vocabulary, and no later perennialist mediation.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-sameness-can-be-the-fingerprint-of-borrowing-a124cfeb0014609d.json:13:    "Gaudapada and Madhyamaka show low strain on non-origination language while retaining high strain around self, Atman, Brahman, and remainder.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-sameness-can-be-the-fingerprint-of-borrowing-a124cfeb0014609d.json:25:  "exact_claim": "Low translation strain between traditions should not be treated as evidence of independent convergence when historical contact is plausible. In entangled cases, low strain may be a trace of borrowing, shared translators, shared polemic, shared training, or homogenized modern vocabulary, so independence must be established by external provenance before strain is allowed to count.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-sameness-can-be-the-fingerprint-of-borrowing-a124cfeb0014609d.json:35:      "expected_observation": "A close coding of Mandukya Karika chapter 4 against MMK and Yogacara sources will find low-strain units concentrated in Buddhist technical or argumentative forms, while high-strain units cluster around Vedantic remainder, Atman, Brahman, Turiya, or consciousness.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-sameness-can-be-the-fingerprint-of-borrowing-a124cfeb0014609d.json:43:      "test_surface": "A/B scoring test using the same claim units, one group strain-only, one group provenance-first.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-sameness-can-be-the-fingerprint-of-borrowing-a124cfeb0014609d.json:73:      "difference": "The candidate turns Smith's methodological warning into a local scoring rule for translation strain: low strain in potentially contacted pairs should not count as independent convergence until provenance is settled.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-sameness-can-be-the-fingerprint-of-borrowing-a124cfeb0014609d.json:103:      "difference": "King supplies the historical and philosophical case; the candidate uses it as a general rule for evaluating translation strain.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-sameness-can-be-the-fingerprint-of-borrowing-a124cfeb0014609d.json:117:      "overlap": "Extremely close on provenance gating, translation strain, false convergence, internal variance, shared translator, borrowing, and modern homogenizing vocabulary.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-sameness-can-be-the-fingerprint-of-borrowing-a124cfeb0014609d.json:172:  "unlike_statement": "Unlike Smith, Sandmel, Freiberger, historical linguistics, source criticism, and prior Lumenary provenance gates, this candidate gives one sharper operational rule: in traditions with plausible contact, low translation strain should count against independent-convergence confidence until external provenance evidence clears the contact confound."
